==English==

===Etymology===
Recorded since 1538, either (for its original color) from Medieval French carnation "person's color or complexion" (probably from {{etyl|la}} [[carnagione]] "flesh color," from Lat Latin [[carnatio]] "fleshiness", from Latin [[caro]] "flesh") or a corruption of [[coronation]] (from [[coronare]] 'to crown', from [[corona]] 'crown'; beacuse of the flower's use in chaplets or from the toothed crown-like look of the petals .

===Pronunciation===
IPA: kɔrˈneɪ.ʃʌn

